Image Classification

Image Analysis Group

June 22, 2018

Introduction

The following report presents the main steps for classifying an image composed by 4 bands derived from the multiespectral camara Mapir in the invoronment of R studio. The first two bands correspond to red and near infrared that are directly sensed by the camera. However, the third corresponds to a vegetation index using the two previous bands and the fourth is the digital surface model (DSM) that is a photogrammetry product.

Importing rasters

The image cover an area of 3.1 Ha and has 30 cm of spatial resolution. In the following lines we will import the raster to the environment of R studio.

setwd("D:/MASTER_GEOTECH_2S/UAS/Classification")
library(raster)
source("functions_lulc.R")
library(sf)
library(tidyverse)
path_wd = "D:/MASTER_GEOTECH_2S/UAS/Classification"
train_data_path = "Training"
raster_data_path = "image/Compositebands30cm.tif"
#Importing raster to obtain infromation about number of bands and size of the image in terms of number of pixels
composition_drone = raster(raster_data_path)
nbands = composition_drone@file@nbands  #Number of bands
#Empty list with 4 elemts where I will store each raster
bands_list = vector("list",nbands)
#Using for loop to store the bands in the list
for(i in 1:nbands)
{
  bands_list[[i]] = raster(raster_data_path,band = i)
}
#stacking raster
bands_data <- stack(bands_list)

Adding training

The training data is composed by 8 shapefiles, each one has an independent random sampling of classes (see below). Each sampling comes in square shape and measures 50 cm by side covering in average 4 pixels. In the next lines, we will import the shapefiles to the environment of R and we will mask the pixels that intersect each group of squares by band.

#Creating a list and a for loop to store the name of the shapefiles that are contained in the training folder
files_shp = list()
i= 1
for(f in list.files(train_data_path)){
    x = substr(f,nchar(f)-3,nchar(f))
    if( x == ".shp"){
      files_shp[i] = paste(train_data_path,f,sep="/")
      i = i + 1
    } 
}
#Creating masks with the polygons of the training
dataset = labeling_vector(files_shp,bands_data) %>% as.data.frame()
#data set with the results of the raster mask
colnames(dataset) = c("x","y","NDVI","DSM","NIR","RED","BLUE","Label")

Once created the dataset, the number of pixels with training is 536. The distribution of number of pixels per class can be found in the following table.

t_samples = table(dataset$Label)
names(t_samples) = c("Asphalt(1)", "Bare_soil(2)", "Bushes(3)", "freshlyCutgrass(4)","Grasslands(5)", "Trees(6)","Water(7)","veg_water(8)" )
print(t_samples)
##         Asphalt(1)       Bare_soil(2)          Bushes(3) 
##                 31                 32                 96 
## freshlyCutgrass(4)      Grasslands(5)           Trees(6) 
##                114                141                 78 
##           Water(7)       veg_water(8) 
##                 38                 16
#converting to sf class
samples_sf = st_as_sf(dataset, coords = c("x", "y"), crs = 32632)

Exploration

Once imported the data in R project, we can plot the each band and the training using the following lines of code:

fun <- function() {
plot(st_geometry(samples_sf), add = TRUE, col = "red", pch = 1, cex =0.2)
}

plot(bands_data,addfun = fun, col= grey((9:0)/10), main=c("NDVI","DSM","NIR","RED","BLUE"))

The range of pixel values for red and near infrared is measured in digital levels, with a range that goes from 89 to 237 for the red, and from 38 to 199 for the NIR. Instead of this, the NDVI comes in float numbers with a range of values between -0.54 and 0.006 and the DSM with values between 51 to 79 meters.

boxplot(dataset[,3:7],col= "bisque")

Understanding patterns in the data

The figure 3 presents the scatter plots of the bands of the training dataset. Essentially, the graphic is showing in the bottom left the dispersion among the values of the 4 bands, and in the top right their respective correlation coefficients. It should be noticed, that colors represent the classes associated to each component of pixel values in the dataset. For example, the brown points, in the graphic NDVI vs DSM, correspond to trees and they are located in the higuest range of the dispersion. This information will be very valuable for the classifier since in spite of the bushes and trees depict more or less the same reflectance (high correlation in the graphic), they have in average different heights.

For NIR an Red we found a strong linear correlation when it comes about vegetation coverages. However, classes such as water, bare soil and asphalt can be separated visually since the belong to the lowest region of the dispersion. This fact can be better explored using NDVI in one of the axis and NIR in the another since the decision of defining what is or not vegetation is a straing line perpendicular to the NIR axis.

pairs(dataset[,3:7], main = "Bands",
      pch = 21, bg =c("grey","yellow","darkgreen","green","orange","brown","blue","violet")[unclass(dataset$Label)],
      lower.panel = panel.smooth, upper.panel = panel.cor)

Partitioning dataset

We randomly separated the dataset into 30% for test and 70% for training.

#data partition
dataset$Label = as.factor(dataset$Label)
#set.seed function makes this analysis repetitible. So we want to work with the same random sampling.
set.seed(123)
#this produce a random number of indices and divide it in two groups.
ind =  sample(2,nrow(dataset), replace =TRUE, prob = c(0.7,0.3))
train = dataset[ind==1,]  
testd = dataset[ind==2,]

Classifiers

We run two classifiers using the same dataset, they are random forest and support vector machine.

Random forest

We run decision tress using the package called caret. The parameters used and tuned for our classifier were two, the number of variables randomly sampled as candidates at each split “mtry” and the number of trees to grow “mtry”. On the one hand, we used mtry equal to two since by convention this values should be the square root of the number of variables in the analysis (4). On the another hand, we used a mtry = 500, which means the branches split into two only when the sample sizes were at least 500 and this was the way we restricted the growth of our trees (tun using function plot(rf)).

In the next lines we will train the classsifier using the 70% of the dataset.

library(caret)
library(randomForest)
rf = randomForest::randomForest(Label~. , data = train[,c(-1,-2)],
                                ntree = 500, 
                                mtry = 2)
#print(rf)
importance(rf)
##      MeanDecreaseGini
## NDVI         88.70767
## DSM         130.70311
## NIR          46.51656
## RED          25.79646
## BLUE         26.66219

“Importance” function extracts by order the level of importance of the variable in the prediction. In this sense, DSM and NDVI are essential in the classification problem.

Once trained the classifier we assess the results using the rest of the data

p1 = predict(rf, testd[,c(-1,-2,-8)])

Looking at the confusion matrix, predictions are quite good in general with an overall accuracy of 0.79% and a range that is still good with a standart deviation of 7%. The are good classification for classes 1(Asphalt), 2(Bare soil), 6 (trees) and 7 (vegetation over water). However, there are some misclassification for classes 3 (bushes) and 5 (grassland), sometimes they are mixed into the rest of the classes that have vegetation. The values of sensitivity also report the previous statement with values under 0.7 for those clases. As we said before, the reason by which the predictor does not often classify correctly those classes is because they are spectrally comparable. However, the improvement in the classification is because the use of DSM leads to the classifier to handle better the differences of those classes, that is mainly heights.

Finally, regardless of the unbalanced frequency for all the classes of the sampling, we find interesting than random forest end up being a good predictor for all of them.

SVM

We run support vector machine using the package called e1071. We use the same number of variables and the same partition of the dataset. We tune two conditions of the classifier, they are the parameters, epsilon in the insensitive-loss function and and the cost of constraints violation. We use by default the radial kernel since is the one giving the best results.

library(e1071)
svm_model1 = e1071::svm(Label~. , data = train[,c(-1,-2)], kernel='radial')

#tunning parameters
tmodel = tune(svm,Label~. , data = train[,c(-1,-2)], 
              ranges = list(epsilon = seq(0,1,0.1), cost = seq(20,40,4)))
#plot(tmodel )
#summary(tmodel)
svm_model2 = tmodel$best.model
#summary(mymodel)

p2 = predict(svm_model2, testd[,c(-1,-2,-8)])
caret::confusionMatrix(p2,testd$Label)

Looking at the confusion matrix again implementing this classifier we can see an overall accuracy that is still good but lower than the one using random forest. Therefore, we will implement the model of random forest for the classification of the complete image.

Mapping classification

Finally, to map the classification we transform all the four bands in a table, where each row represent the pixel values of each band.

dataset_bands = values(bands_data) #%>% as.tibble()
colnames(dataset_bands) = c("NDVI","DSM","NIR","RED","BLUE")
p3 = predict(rf, dataset_bands)  %>% as.numeric()
new_raster = bands_list[[1]]
values(new_raster) = p3
#col_raster = grey((9:0)/10)
col_fun = c("grey","yellow","darkgreen","green","orange","brown","blue","violet")
plot(new_raster, col =  col_fun, legend= FALSE)
legend("topright", legend = names(t_samples), fill = col_fun, cex = 0.6)

Concerning the post processing, the generalization and vectorization are done using Qgis. Therefore, we export the previous results using the following last of code.
